00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:02.980
Hey wassup guys! My name is The Cherno. Welcome back to my C++

00:00:02.980 --> 00:00:05.460
series. Today we gonna take what we learn our

00:00:05.475 --> 00:00:08.375
classes so far and haven't gone actually writing a class from scratch.

00:00:08.375 --> 00:00:11.405
Am not gonna take it too far today, we're not gonna write some

00:00:11.405 --> 00:00:14.465
massive complicated class. We're just gonna write a basic log class

00:00:14.465 --> 00:00:17.920
that should demonstrate some of the basic phases we have learnt so far.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:23.540
Over the next few episodes we're going to keep working on this class and so introduce new concepts  so you get to see the process

00:00:23.540 --> 00:00:26.460
and the difference from a basic version of class

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:29.540
to a more advanced version that does the same thing but  could be considered as a

00:00:29.540 --> 00:00:30.040
better card.But first this video

00:00:51.355 --> 00:00:54.265
 

00:00:54.265 --> 00:00:56.885
 

00:00:56.885 --> 00:00:59.885
Alright, so let's talk about this Log class that we're about to write

00:00:59.885 --> 00:01:02.735
What is Log class? So this Log class is going to be a way

00:01:02.735 --> 00:01:05.335
for us to manage a log messages . So another way it's

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:07.660
messages or information that we want our program

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:08.800
to print to the console.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.840
This is usually used for debugging purposes and really helps us out

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:14.760
in out game or application, if we wanna kinda see what's going on

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.840
and just print the status of things into our console

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:21.540
because the console in our application is really like an information dump

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:24.980
which we can use to just print out what's going on

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:27.240
 

00:01:27.245 --> 00:01:30.215
 

00:01:30.215 --> 00:01:33.415
in our game or something that might be a little

00:01:33.415 --> 00:01:35.265
different and it might not work all the time

00:01:35.265 --> 00:01:38.320
because if there is something wrong with our graphics rendering system or something like that

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:41.420
we might not get those messages printing properly, however,

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:44.455
a console? is something that basically is built into the operating system

00:01:44.455 --> 00:01:47.535
so we can pretty much guarantee that will always work

00:01:47.535 --> 00:01:50.325
I also really like the idea of using a log class

00:01:50.325 --> 00:01:53.435
as an example because a logging system can be

00:01:53.435 --> 00:01:55.505
as simple or as complicated as you wanted to be

00:01:55.645 --> 00:01:58.705
it's amazing how complicated some log

00:01:58.705 --> 00:02:01.385
systems are like. I am talking 1000 of lines

00:02:01.385 --> 00:02:04.075
of code just to print out to the console and

00:02:04.075 --> 00:02:06.525
it's so so important for debugging and for development

00:02:06.525 --> 00:02:09.525
that it is definitely worth spending time on that.

